---

<Base
  title="How to Build Your First CrewAI Agent in Python (Beginner Tutorial) | Tenure"
  description="A step-by-step beginner tutorial for building your first working agent with CrewAI in Python, from install to your first kickoff()."
>

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": "How to Build Your First CrewAI Agent in Python (Beginner Tutorial)",
  "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "Tenure", "url": "https://tenureai.dev" },
  "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "Tenure", "url": "https://tenureai.dev" },
  "url": "https://tenureai.dev/writing/how-to-build-a-crewai-agent-in-python",
  "description": "A step-by-step beginner tutorial for building your first working agent with CrewAI in Python, from install to your first kickoff().",
  "datePublished": "2026-07-16",
  "dateModified": "2026-07-16"
}
</script>

<section class="essay-hero">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="uc-breadcrumb">
      <a href="/writing">Writing</a>
      <span class="uc-breadcrumb-sep">›</span>
      <span>Tutorials</span>
    </div>
    <span class="label" style="margin-top:1.5rem; display:inline-block;">CrewAI</span>
    <h1>How to Build Your First CrewAI Agent in Python (Beginner Tutorial)</h1>
    <p class="hero-sub-title" style="margin-top:1rem;">
      You do not need a multi-agent pipeline to get started. This tutorial builds
      one CrewAI agent with one job, runs it, and explains every line, so you can
      go from a blank file to a working agent in about ten minutes.
    </p>
    <div class="essay-meta">
      <span class="essay-meta-item">Tenure tutorials</span>
      <span class="essay-meta-sep">·</span>
      <span class="essay-meta-item">~6 min read</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="essay-section" style="border-top:1px solid var(--border); border-bottom:1px solid var(--border); background:var(--surface);">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="tldr-box">
      <h3>TL;DR</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>A CrewAI agent needs three things: a <code>role</code>, a <code>goal</code>, and a <code>backstory</code>.</li>
        <li>Install with <code>pip install crewai</code>, then set an API key for whichever LLM you want to use.</li>
        <li>One agent plus one <code>Task</code> plus one <code>Crew</code> is enough to run something real. You do not need multiple agents to start.</li>
        <li>You call <code>crew.kickoff()</code> to run it, and read the result off <code>result.raw</code>.</li>
        <li>Keep the first agent's job narrow. Add tools, memory, and teammates once the simple version works.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="essay-section" style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);">
  <div class="container essay-prose">
    <span class="label">The basics</span>
    <h2>What a CrewAI agent actually is</h2>
    <p>
      In CrewAI, an agent is not a vague concept. It is a Python object with a
      specific job description. You give it a role to play, a goal to work
      toward, and a backstory that shapes how it approaches that goal. Under the
      hood, CrewAI turns those three fields into a system prompt for an LLM, then
      wraps that LLM with the ability to call tools, follow a task, and return a
      final answer.
    </p>
    <p>
      Think of it like writing a one-paragraph job posting instead of a full
      prompt engineering document. "You are a Research Analyst. Your goal is to
      find accurate information quickly. You are detail-oriented and always cite
      your sources." CrewAI takes that job posting and runs it.
    </p>
    <div class="essay-callout">
      <p>
        For your first agent, resist the urge to add tools, memory, or a second
        agent. A single agent with a single task is the fastest way to confirm
        your setup works before you add moving parts.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="essay-section" style="background:var(--surface); border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);">
  <div class="container essay-prose">
    <span class="label">Setup</span>
    <h2>Install CrewAI and set your API key</h2>
    <p>
      You will need Python 3.10 or newer. Create a virtual environment if you do
      not already have one for this project, then install the package.
    </p>

    <div class="code-block">
      <div class="code-block__header">
        <div class="code-block__dots">
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--red"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--yellow"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--green"></span>
        </div>
        <span class="code-block__filename">terminal</span>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block__body" is:raw>
        <pre><span class="c-key">python</span> <span class="c-str">-m</span> <span class="c-key">venv</span> <span class="c-key">.venv</span>
<span class="c-key">source</span> <span class="c-key">.venv/bin/activate</span>  <span class="c-dim"># On Windows: .venv\Scripts\activate</span>

<span class="c-key">pip</span> <span class="c-str">install</span> <span class="c-key">crewai</span></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>
      CrewAI defaults to OpenAI's models, so the simplest path is to set an
      <code>OPENAI_API_KEY</code> environment variable. If you would rather use
      a different provider, you can pass a specific model string to the
      <code>llm</code> parameter later, but for this tutorial we will stick with
      the default.
    </p>

    <div class="code-block">
      <div class="code-block__header">
        <div class="code-block__dots">
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--red"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--yellow"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--green"></span>
        </div>
        <span class="code-block__filename">terminal</span>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block__body" is:raw>
        <pre><span class="c-key">export</span> <span class="c-key">OPENAI_API_KEY</span>=<span class="c-str">"sk-..."</span>  <span class="c-dim"># On Windows: setx OPENAI_API_KEY "sk-..."</span></pre>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="essay-section" style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);">
  <div class="container essay-prose">
    <span class="label">Walkthrough</span>
    <h2>Build the agent in four small steps</h2>
    <p>
      For this tutorial, the agent's job is simple on purpose: take a topic and
      write a short, plain-English summary of it. No tools, no research, no
      second agent. Just one job, done well.
    </p>

    <div class="flow-grid">
      <div class="flow-card">
        <span class="flow-step">1</span>
        <h3>Define the agent</h3>
        <p>Give it a role, a goal, and a backstory. This is the entire personality and job description.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-card">
        <span class="flow-step">2</span>
        <h3>Write the task</h3>
        <p>A task is the specific instruction and the shape of the output you expect back.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-card">
        <span class="flow-step">3</span>
        <h3>Assemble the crew</h3>
        <p>A crew connects your agent to its task, even when there is only one of each.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-card">
        <span class="flow-step">4</span>
        <h3>Kick it off</h3>
        <p>Call <code>kickoff()</code> and CrewAI runs the agent against the task and returns a result.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>Step 1: Define the agent</h3>
    <p>
      Import <code>Agent</code> from <code>crewai</code> and describe the job. Keep the
      backstory short. It is context for the model, not a creative writing exercise.
    </p>

    <div class="code-block">
      <div class="code-block__header">
        <div class="code-block__dots">
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--red"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--yellow"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--green"></span>
        </div>
        <span class="code-block__filename">agent.py</span>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block__body" is:raw>
        <pre><span class="c-key">from</span> crewai <span class="c-key">import</span> Agent, Task, Crew

writer = Agent(
    role=<span class="c-str">"Content Writer"</span>,
    goal=<span class="c-str">"Write clear, friendly summaries that a beginner can understand"</span>,
    backstory=(
        <span class="c-str">"You explain technical topics to curious non-experts. "</span>
        <span class="c-str">"You avoid jargon and never assume prior knowledge."</span>
    ),
    verbose=<span class="c-bool">True</span>,
)</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>
      That is a working agent. It does not do anything yet, because an agent
      without a task has nothing to act on.
    </p>

    <h3>Step 2: Write the task</h3>
    <p>
      A <code>Task</code> pairs an instruction with an expected output shape,
      and points at the agent responsible for it. The <code>{'{topic}'}</code>
      placeholder gets filled in when you run the crew, so you can reuse the
      same agent for different topics without rewriting the task.
    </p>

    <div class="code-block">
      <div class="code-block__header">
        <div class="code-block__dots">
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--red"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--yellow"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--green"></span>
        </div>
        <span class="code-block__filename">agent.py (continued)</span>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block__body" is:raw>
        <pre>summarize_task = Task(
    description=<span class="c-str">"Write a 3-paragraph summary of {topic} for a total beginner."</span>,
    expected_output=<span class="c-str">"A friendly, jargon-free, 3-paragraph explanation."</span>,
    agent=writer,
)</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>Step 3: Assemble the crew</h3>
    <p>
      A <code>Crew</code> is what actually runs. Even with a single agent and a
      single task, CrewAI still expects them wrapped in a crew.
    </p>

    <div class="code-block">
      <div class="code-block__header">
        <div class="code-block__dots">
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--red"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--yellow"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--green"></span>
        </div>
        <span class="code-block__filename">agent.py (continued)</span>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block__body" is:raw>
        <pre>crew = Crew(
    agents=[writer],
    tasks=[summarize_task],
)</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>Step 4: Kick it off</h3>
    <p>
      Call <code>crew.kickoff()</code> and pass the inputs your task's placeholders
      need. The result object gives you the final text on <code>result.raw</code>.
    </p>

    <div class="code-block">
      <div class="code-block__header">
        <div class="code-block__dots">
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--red"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--yellow"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--green"></span>
        </div>
        <span class="code-block__filename">agent.py (continued)</span>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block__body" is:raw>
        <pre>result = crew.kickoff(inputs={<span class="c-str">"topic"</span>: <span class="c-str">"how neural networks learn"</span>})
print(result.raw)</pre>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="essay-section" style="background:var(--surface); border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);">
  <div class="container essay-prose">
    <span class="label">Full example</span>
    <h2>The whole file, in one place</h2>
    <p>
      Here is everything above combined into a single script you can copy,
      save as <code>agent.py</code>, and run with <code>python agent.py</code>.
    </p>

    <div class="code-block">
      <div class="code-block__header">
        <div class="code-block__dots">
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--red"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--yellow"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--green"></span>
        </div>
        <span class="code-block__filename">agent.py</span>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block__body" is:raw>
        <pre><span class="c-key">from</span> crewai <span class="c-key">import</span> Agent, Task, Crew

writer = Agent(
    role=<span class="c-str">"Content Writer"</span>,
    goal=<span class="c-str">"Write clear, friendly summaries that a beginner can understand"</span>,
    backstory=(
        <span class="c-str">"You explain technical topics to curious non-experts. "</span>
        <span class="c-str">"You avoid jargon and never assume prior knowledge."</span>
    ),
    verbose=<span class="c-bool">True</span>,
)

summarize_task = Task(
    description=<span class="c-str">"Write a 3-paragraph summary of {topic} for a total beginner."</span>,
    expected_output=<span class="c-str">"A friendly, jargon-free, 3-paragraph explanation."</span>,
    agent=writer,
)

crew = Crew(
    agents=[writer],
    tasks=[summarize_task],
)

result = crew.kickoff(inputs={<span class="c-str">"topic"</span>: <span class="c-str">"how neural networks learn"</span>})
print(result.raw)</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p style="margin-top:1.5rem;">
      Run it, and CrewAI will print its reasoning as it goes (thanks to
      <code>verbose=True</code>), then print the final three-paragraph summary
      at the end. Change the <code>topic</code> input and rerun it to summarize
      something else, no other code changes needed.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="essay-section" style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);">
  <div class="container essay-prose">
    <span class="label">Common mistakes</span>
    <h2>Where beginners usually get stuck</h2>
    <ul style="line-height:1.9; color:var(--muted);">
      <li><strong>Forgetting the API key.</strong> If <code>OPENAI_API_KEY</code> is not set, the agent fails before it does anything. Check it is exported in the same terminal session you run the script from.</li>
      <li><strong>Writing a vague goal.</strong> "Be helpful" tells the model nothing. "Write clear, friendly summaries that a beginner can understand" tells it exactly what good output looks like.</li>
      <li><strong>Skipping <code>expected_output</code>.</strong> This field is what keeps the agent's response in a predictable shape. Without it, you get inconsistent formatting from run to run.</li>
      <li><strong>Adding tools and a second agent on day one.</strong> Get the single-agent version working first. Every extra tool or teammate is one more thing that can silently misfire.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="essay-section" style="background:var(--surface);">
  <div class="container essay-prose">
    <span class="label">Next steps</span>
    <h2>Once this works, what to add next</h2>
    <p>
      From here, the natural next steps are giving the agent a tool (like a web
      search tool from <code>crewai_tools</code>) so it can look things up instead
      of relying only on what the model already knows, and adding a second agent
      with a different role so one can research while the other writes.
    </p>
    <p>
      One thing worth planning for early: as soon as an agent starts making
      decisions instead of just generating text (searching before it answers,
      choosing whether to escalate, deciding something is out of scope) it gets
      much harder to tell whether it is behaving correctly just by reading the
      final output. That is a good problem to have, and a different tutorial's
      worth of solving.
    </p>

    <div class="essay-cta-row">
      <a href="https://docs.crewai.com/en/concepts/agents" class="btn-primary mr-2" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        Full CrewAI agent docs →
      </a>
      <a href="https://github.com/crewAIInc/crewAI" class="btn-secondary mr-2" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        CrewAI on GitHub
      </a>
      <a href="/writing" class="btn-secondary">
        More from Tenure
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

